England":"Wiltshire, England","All Canning, Wiltshire, England":"All Cannings, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Masselin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Lucien, Germain, Jacques, Normand, Amedee, Fernand, Gilles, Laurent, Alphee, Benoit.","French: from an Old French personal name, a pet form of <i>Asse</i>; see   Ace   1. Compare   Ashline  .","Altered form of French   Ancelin  . Compare   Ashland   3,   Ashley   2, and   Aslin   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ace","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>Ace</i>, <i>Asse</i>, or <i>Asce</i>, all from the ancient Germanic male personal name <i>Az(z)o</i>, <i>Atso</i>, <i>Adso</i>, or possibly the female personal name <i>Aza</i>. These were pet forms of ancient Germanic compound names formed with <i>adal-</i> ‘noble’, such as <i>Adalbert</i> (later   Albert  ) and <i>Adalheidis</i> (later <i>Alice</i>; see   Allis  )."]},{"name":"Ashline","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Asselin   1.","History: Bearers of the surname <i>Ashline</i> are descendants of one or another of the brothers Jacques and David Asselin from France (see   Asselin  )."]},{"name":"Aslin","meanings":["English: from the Middle English male personal name <i>Asselyn</i> (from Old French <i>Acelin</i>, <i>Ascelin</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Azilin</i>). There was also a feminine form, <i>A(s)celine</i>.","Altered form of   Asselin   2, a surname of French origin.","Swedish (<b>Åslin</b>): topographic or ornamental name from <i>ås</i> ‘ridge’ + the suffix <i>-lin</i>, derived from Latin <i>-(l)inius</i> ‘relating to’. Compare   Ashlin   and   Oslin  ."]},{"name":"Ashley","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places (especially in southern and central England) named Ashley, from Old English <i>æsc</i> ‘ash’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Americanized form of French Canadian   Asselin   2.","In some cases also an Americanized form of German   Eschler  ."]}]},{"name":"Maslyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Maslin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Maslin","meanings":["English (mainly Wiltshire and Gloucestershire): from the Old French and Middle English personal names <i>Mazelin</i> (male) or <i>Mazeline</i> (female), which are double diminutives of ancient Germanic <i>Mazo</i>, <i>Matso</i> (male) and <i>Maza</i>, <i>Matsa</i> (female). These are probably pet forms of ancient Germanic names such as <i>Mathalgar</i> (see   Major  ), which have <i>mathal-</i> ‘speech’ as their first element, but the female name might also be a pet form of <i>Matild(a)</i> (see   Tillett  )."]}]},{"name":"Charles","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Germanic word, <i>karl</i>, meaning ‘free man’, akin to Old English <i>ceorl</i> ‘man’. The name, Latin form <i>Carolus</i>, owed its popularity in medieval Europe to the Frankish leader  Charlemagne  (  ?742–814 ), who in  800  established himself as Holy Roman Emperor. His name (Latin <i>Carolus Magnus</i>) means ‘Charles the Great’. <i>Carolus</i>—or <i>Karl</i>, the German form—was a common name among Frankish leaders, including Charlemagne's grandfather  Charles Martel  (  688–741 ). <i>Charles</i> is the French form. The name occurs occasionally in medieval Britain as <i>Karolus</i> or <i>Carolus</i>; it had a certain vogue in West Yorkshire from the 1400s, particularly among gentry families. The form <i>Charles</i> was chosen by  Mary Queen  of Scots (  1542–87 ), who had been brought up in France, for her son, <i>Charles James</i> (  1566–1625 ), who became  King James VI  of Scotland and, from  1603 ,  James I  of England. His son and grandson both reigned as  King Charles , and the name thus became established in the 17th century both in the Stuart royal house and among English and Scottish supporters of the Stuart monarchy. In the 18th century it was to some extent favoured, along with   James  , by Jacobites, supporters of the exiled Stuarts, opposed to the Hanoverian monarchy, especially in the Highlands of Scotland. In the 19th century the popularity of the name was further enhanced by romanticization of the story of ‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’, leader of the  1745  rebellion."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":29,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":38,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Charles Masselin Maslyn Maslinge was born about 1520, in Wiltshire, England. He had at least 1 son with Martha. He died after 1561, in Marlborough, Wiltshire, England."},"et":{"about 1520–after 1561":"umbes 1520–pärast 1561","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","1540–1590":"1540–1590","1520–1561":"1520–1561","1558":"1558","1520":"1520","1540":"1540","1561":"1561","about 1520":"umbes 1520","after 1561":"pärast 1561","1590":"1590","1549":"1549","Marlborough, Wiltshire, England":"Marlborough, Wiltshire, England","Wilts